# Keep README and PRIVACY Docs Up to Date

After completing any code changes, review whether `README.md` and `PRIVACY.md` need to be updated.

## When to Update README.md

- New features or functionality added
- Existing features modified or removed
- Configuration, setup steps, or dependencies changed
- API or usage instructions affected
- Project structure changed (new files/folders)

## When to Update PRIVACY.md

- Browser permissions changed (added, removed, or modified)
- `manifest` permission fields changed (`permissions`, `optional_permissions`, `host_permissions`, `optional_host_permissions`)
- Data collection scope changed (what data is collected)
- Data usage changed (why and how data is processed)
- Data storage/retention changed (where and for how long)
- Third-party services changed that may receive user data
- User controls changed (opt-in/opt-out, deletion, access requests)

## When NOT to Update

- Pure refactors with no behavioral change
- Bug fixes that don't affect documented behavior
- Internal implementation details not mentioned in public docs

## Process

1. Read the current `README.md` and `PRIVACY.md`
2. Compare both files against the changes just made
3. If user-facing behavior/setup changed, update `README.md`
4. If permissions/data practices changed, update `PRIVACY.md`
5. If any `manifest` permission field changed, updating `PRIVACY.md` is mandatory (no exceptions)
6. Keep each file consistent with its existing style and structure
